{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"alias":"mellow-coke-veto","description":"`rebar review-plan` reports `signature` present (the JSON `signature` field is non-null, and\nbatch tooling reads `signed=True`) even when the **verdict is BLOCK**. The documented contract\nis that it \"signs a plan-review attestation on a **non-blocking PASS**\" â€” so a BLOCK verdict\nshould NOT carry a passing signed attestation. Either the signing-on-BLOCK is a bug, or the\n`signature` field means something other than \"passing attestation\"; either way it is misleading,\nbecause the signature is meant to be the trustworthy proof-of-PASS that downstream gates (the\nclaim gate) and CI rely on. A consumer that checks \"is there a signature?\" to decide\nclaimability would be misled by a signed BLOCK.\n\n## Reproduction Steps\n1. Author a ticket whose plan trips a blocking criterion (or use any ticket the four-pass gate\n   BLOCKs).\n2. Run `rebar review-plan <id> --output json` (default source = attested, signing on).\n3. Inspect the result JSON: `verdict` and `signature`.\n\n## Expected\n- On `verdict == BLOCK`, no passing attestation is signed â€” `signature` is null/absent (or the\n  field is unambiguously labeled as a non-passing attestation), so \"has signature\" reliably\n  means \"passed\".\n\n## Actual\n- Observed repeatedly this session: tickets with `verdict=BLOCK` returned `signature` populated\n  (`signed=True`). Concretely, Round-2/3/4 runs on the S4/S6/S7 d251 children showed e.g.\n  `s6: BLOCK block=6 ... signed=True` and `s4: BLOCK block=2 ... signed=True` â€” a signature on a\n  BLOCK.\n\n## Notes\n- Inferred from the JSON `signature` field, not the signing internals â€” possible the field is\n  populated-but-not-a-passing-attestation; that distinction is exactly what's unclear and should\n  be made explicit. Surfaced while dogfooding the plan-review gate on epic d251 (alto-fruit-punch).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `rebar review-plan <id>` on a BLOCK verdict does NOT emit a passing signed attestation\n      (either `signature` is null/absent on BLOCK, or the field/type is explicitly distinct from\n      a passing attestation and documented as such).\n- [ ] `verify_signature` / the claim gate cannot be satisfied by an attestation produced on a\n      BLOCK verdict (a BLOCKed plan is never claimable on the strength of its signature).\n- [ ] The behavior is documented (docs/plan-review-gate.md): exactly when a signature is emitted\n      and what its presence guarantees.\n- [ ] A regression test asserts: BLOCK verdict -> no passing signature; PASS verdict -> signature present.","id":"3a70-3ade-6673-4a91","parent_id":"","priority":2,"tags":["plan-review","llm","gate"],"ticket_type":"bug","title":"plan-review: signed attestation emitted on BLOCK verdict (signature should mean PASS)"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1782699755763088001,"uuid":"937344d9-d251-4e50-bd48-62b81a855716"}